node.accessibility_caption: Affordable Self-care: set more realistic expectations about how long things take to get done.

node.text:
Let’s call it optimism...or poor planning. I always think I will be able to get things done a lot faster than is realistic.
.
And what happens? I get impatient and frustrated. I get stressed or irritable. I end up running late. Others of us might get self-critical or shaming.
.
It’s actually fairly simple to avoid all of those negative feelings. It’s about setting more realistic expectations, goals, and timeframes.
.
And as a parent, it’s about learning that things always take longer with kids in tow...and that it’s not really a problem if we adapt to the situation instead of assuming that the situation will adapt to us.
.

node.accessibility_caption: authenticity doesn’t mean you are an open book.

node.text:
You still get to have boundaries. You still get a say in what people know about you.
.
As a therapist, my goal is to be fully present and my most genuine self with my clients. Does that mean they must know the details of my life, my past? No way.
.
And you know what? The process is the better for it. They don’t get tripped up in worrying about my stuff and are better able to figure out their own.
.
Caption [authenticity doesn’t mean you are an open book.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: sometimes people do you a favor when they reject you.

node.text:
No one wins everyone over.
.
It sucks to get rejected...from jobs and schools...by people you want to date or be friends with. Trust me though. Sometimes it’s better to be rejected.
.
They might be seeing something you don’t that will get in the way later. Maybe they tells you they really want a long-term relationship (like you) when they really don’t. Or, that school can tell they aren’t a great fit. It’s better to be rejected early and shift to another plan, than it is to find out when those other options are gone.
.
Has this happened to you?
.

.

node.accessibility_caption: affordable self-care: keep a list of coping strategies and reminders that have been helpful to you.

node.text:
And keep them in a handy place.
.
What are helpful reminders and coping practices for you?
.
Here are some of mine:
1. Take a few slow, gentle breaths.
2. Drink a glass of water.
3. Walk or do some kind of exercise.
4. Talk to a friend or my husband.
5. Take a break.
6. Remind myself that this feeling won’t last forever.
.
Caption [affordable self-care: keep a list of coping strategies and reminders that have been helpful to you.]
.

node.accessibility_caption: Affordable Self-care: allow people to help you.

node.text:
Ok, so maybe not the people who attach manipulative strings to their help. Their help is often more trouble than it’s worth.
.
Accept the help that the rest of us offer.
.
•Let us open the door for you.
•Let people bring you food when you are sick.
•Let people do their share of the group project.
.
We undermine people’s efforts to help (and connect) when we reject their offers...or go back and correct what they have done. Just accept the help and move on.
.

.

node.text:
So many transitions.
So many changes.
.
It seems like as soon as we start to settle into a sense of routine and normalcy, the world shifts yet again.
.
Hang in there.
Go easy on yourself.
Rest when you can.
.

node.text:
Today is the last day to get my e-courses at 40% off. I’m retiring my New Therapist bundle, so now is the time to get yours.

•Even if you have a lot of experience with it.
•Even if they are your parent, your child, your friend, your partner.
•Even if...no matter what.
.
It doesn’t mean you are cutting off the connection between you and them. It means shifting to a healthier connection.
.
Hop off the rollercoaster, but stay near by.
.
It makes me think of any parent with a young child. In the course of a day, you can expect many emotional highs and lows. The goal is to stay grounded in your own body and connected to your child. It means honoring our limits and taking breaks when we need them.
.

.

node.text:
Who you are as a person is so much more complicated than a test score.
.
It’s important to be on the lookout for all-or-nothing thinking and the idea that 2nd place is another word for “first loser” (what song is that from?!).
.
People will be better than you at some things. You will be better than them at others. It doesn’t mean either of you are failures.
.

node.accessibility_caption: it’s easier to honor your limits when you actually know what they are.

node.text:
My courses and bundles are 40% off until the end of July. I am likely going to archive these courses and launch new ones. If you are interested in one of the courses, now is the time to get it!
・・・
“I don’t work past 6.”
“No phones during supper.”
“I don’t date coworkers.”
“I take at least 2 rest days from running each week.”
“2 drinks is my limit.”
.
We all have limits, whether we are aware of them or not.
.
For me, I find it easier to stick to mine when I have them figured out ahead of time. In the moment, I’m less likely to feel guilty, because I know that I’m not singling that person out...I’m not playing favorites. I’m just following the limits that I know help me to take care of myself and avoid burnout.
.
